paragraphs.p:
One set of prototypical examples of vector spaces are the collections of vectors we have been studying in Chapters: \R^2, \R^3, and the higher-dimensional spaces \R^n, n\ge 4. In these spaces,
adding vectors or scalar multiplying a vector results in a vector in the same space, satisfying Axiom A and Axiom S;
the zero vector is \zerovec = (0,0,\dotsc,0) as usual;
the negative of a vector is the parallel vector of the same length in the opposite direction; and
we know that the rest of the axioms hold true from our knowledge of vector algebra in these spaces ().
In Part of , we discovered that even the collection of real numbers itself can be considered as a vector space. We might think of this space as \R^1, and visualize its vectors as directed line segments lying along the real number line.

Another set of prototypical examples of vectors spaces are the collections of matrices of a given size, \matrixring_{m \times n}(\R). But these matrix spaces represent our first expansion of the word vector to include other kinds of objects since all ten axioms hold true here, we can justifiably refer to any matrix, of any size, as a vector. In these spaces,
adding matrices or scalar multiplying a matrix does not change its size, so these operations always result in a vector in the same space, satisfying Axiom A and Axiom S;
the zero vector is the zero matrix of the appropriate size;
the negative of a vector is the matrix of the same size where all the entries are the negatives of those of the original matrix; and
we know that the rest of the axioms hold true from our knowledge of matrix algebra ().
